PRD — QR Storefront SaaS MVP (Agent-Ready)
Version: 1.0
Prepared for: Coding agent implementation
Product Type: SaaS web app
Primary Stack: Next.js + TypeScript + PostgreSQL + Prisma + Tailwind + Auth.js/Clerk + Cloudinary
Architecture Style: Modular monolith

1. PRODUCT OVERVIEW
1.1 Product Summary
Build a multi-tenant SaaS web application that allows local business owners to create a public digital storefront accessible via a QR code and public URL.
Each shop owner can:
create and manage one or more shops
configure shop details and branding
create categories and products/services
create seasonal/custom collections (e.g. Holi Specials, Diwali Collection)
publish a public storefront page
generate and download QR codes for the storefront
allow customers to browse items and send a cart to WhatsApp
view basic analytics (paid plan only)
Super admins can:
manage all users and shops
assign plans
grant manual free trial durations (e.g. 1/2/3 months)
create shops on behalf of owners
suspend/activate shops
impersonate owners with audit logs
Customers can:
scan QR or open public URL
browse shop items
search/filter by category or collection
add items to cart
send cart via WhatsApp to shop owner
call the shop
open location link
share the storefront link

2. MVP GOAL
2.1 Primary Goal
Deliver a fully functional MVP that supports:
owner self-serve onboarding
admin-assisted onboarding
catalog management
public storefront
QR generation
WhatsApp cart ordering
plan gating (Free vs Paid)
basic analytics
superadmin controls
2.2 Target Scale (MVP)
100–1000 shops
10k–100k monthly storefront visits / QR scans
1–500 items per shop depending on plan

3. USER ROLES
3.1 Roles
SUPER_ADMIN
OWNER
PUBLIC_VISITOR (unauthenticated customer)
No staff roles in MVP.

4. CORE FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS

5. OWNER FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
5.1 Authentication
Owner must be able to:
sign up
log in
log out
reset password (if email/password auth)
access owner dashboard only
Acceptance Criteria
Owner cannot access admin routes
Unauthenticated users cannot access owner dashboard
Owner sessions persist securely

5.2 Owner Onboarding Wizard
After first login, owner should be guided through a multi-step onboarding flow.
Steps
Basic account confirmation
Select business type
F&B
Retail
Service
Mixed
Create first shop
shop name
slug
phone
WhatsApp number
address (optional)
maps link (optional)
Branding
logo (optional)
cover image (optional)
primary color
Add first category
Add first 1–3 items
Publish shop
View/download QR
Acceptance Criteria
Owner can skip optional steps (branding, address)
Owner must complete minimum required fields before publish
Owner can exit onboarding and resume later
Onboarding status stored persistently

5.3 Multi-Shop Support
Owner may have multiple shops in backend from day 1.
MVP UI
UI can primarily optimize for one shop, but must allow creating additional shops.
Acceptance Criteria
Owner can create at least 1 shop on Free plan
Shop limit is plan-gated
Owner cannot access shops belonging to another owner

6. SHOP MANAGEMENT REQUIREMENTS
6.1 Shop Entity
Each shop must support:
Required Fields
name
unique slug
business type
phone
WhatsApp number
Optional Fields
description
email
address
city
state
country (default India for new shops)
postal code
Google Maps URL
logo
cover image
primary brand color
Operational Fields
status: draft / published / suspended / archived
open/closed manual toggle
business hours enabled toggle
last updated timestamp
last published timestamp
Acceptance Criteria
Slug must be unique globally
Slug must be URL-safe
Published shops must have required minimum fields
Suspended shops should not be publicly accessible

6.2 Shop Settings
Owner can configure:
open/closed manual status
business hours
offer banner
contact actions
storefront visibility settings
Acceptance Criteria
If manually closed, storefront shows “Closed”
If business hours enabled, status can be derived by time (optional MVP enhancement)
Offer banner should show on public storefront when active

7. CATALOG MANAGEMENT REQUIREMENTS

7.1 Categories
Categories are structural groupings for items.
Examples
Sweets
Snacks
Beverages
Men’s Wear
Sarees
Category Fields
name (required)
slug (auto-generated)
description (optional)
display order
active/inactive
Rules
Category belongs to exactly one shop
Category names do not need to be globally unique
Display order controls storefront ordering
Acceptance Criteria
Owner can create/edit/delete categories
Deleting a category with items should either:
be blocked, OR
require reassignment (recommended: block in MVP)

7.2 Collections
Collections are seasonal/custom/marketing groupings.
Examples
Holi Specials
Diwali Collection
New Arrivals
Wedding Specials
Summer Coolers
Collection Fields
name (required)
slug
description (optional)
type (SEASONAL, OCCASION, FEATURED, CUSTOM)
cover image (optional)
display order
active/inactive
starts_at (optional)
ends_at (optional)
Rules
Collection belongs to exactly one shop
An item may belong to multiple collections
Collections are independent from categories
Acceptance Criteria
Owner can create/edit/delete collections
Owner can add existing items to collections
Owner can optionally create new item directly from collection workflow
Public storefront can display collections separately from categories

7.3 Items
Items represent products or services.
Item Types
PRODUCT
SERVICE
Required Fields
name
item type
price
category (recommended required for product, optional for service)
shop association
Optional Fields
old price
description
image
availability toggle
featured flag
bestseller flag
display order
dietary type (for F&B only: veg/non-veg/egg/na)
Business Rules
Item belongs to one shop
Item can belong to one primary category
Item can belong to zero or more collections
Item must be hidden from storefront if:
shop unpublished
item inactive
item unavailable and configured to hide unavailable items (optional later)
Default behavior in MVP:
unavailable items remain visible with “Out of Stock”
Acceptance Criteria
Owner can create/edit/delete items
Owner can upload image
Owner can toggle availability
Owner can mark featured/bestseller
Owner can reorder items manually or via display order field

8. PLAN / SUBSCRIPTION REQUIREMENTS
8.1 Plan Types (MVP)
Free Plan
1 shop
up to 25 items
up to 3 categories
up to 2 collections
platform branding/watermark enabled
no advanced analytics
no PDF export
limited customization
Paid Monthly Plan
higher item limit (e.g. 500)
more shops (e.g. 3 or configurable)
unlimited categories
unlimited collections
analytics enabled
PDF export enabled
no watermark
custom branding enabled
Custom Admin Trial / Promo
Admin can manually grant:
1 month
2 months
3 months
custom start/end dates

8.2 Plan Enforcement
Plan limits must be enforced:
in backend validation
in API mutations
in UI (show warnings/upgrade prompts)
Gated Features
max number of shops
max number of items
max number of categories
max number of collections
analytics visibility
watermark removal
PDF export availability
custom branding controls
Acceptance Criteria
Owner cannot exceed limits via direct API call
UI must clearly show plan limits when reached
Admin can override by changing plan/subscription

9. PUBLIC STOREFRONT REQUIREMENTS
9.1 Public Route
Public storefront must be accessible via:
/s/[slug]
Example:
/s/sweet-house-lko
Acceptance Criteria
Published shops only
Suspended/archived shops return not found or suspended state page
Route is mobile-first optimized

9.2 Public Storefront UI Sections
Must include:
Header
shop logo
shop name
description (optional)
open/closed status
last updated timestamp
Banner Area
offer/announcement banner (if active)
Actions
call shop
WhatsApp inquiry/order
share link
map/directions (if available)
Browsing
category tabs or sections
collection highlights
search bar
featured items section (optional if items exist)
Item Cards
image (if available)
name
price
old price (strikethrough)
short description (optional)
availability state
add to cart
Footer
platform watermark on free plan
optional “Powered by ...”
Acceptance Criteria
Must load fast on mobile
Must work without login
Must gracefully handle shops with no image
Must gracefully handle shops with no collections
Must support up to 500 items without UI breaking

10. CART + WHATSAPP ORDER REQUIREMENTS
10.1 Cart Behavior
Public visitor can:
add items to cart
adjust quantity
remove items
optionally add customer note
generate WhatsApp message
Cart State
client-side only for MVP
no persistent server-side order storage required in MVP

10.2 WhatsApp Order Message
On clicking “Order on WhatsApp”, app should open WhatsApp deep link with pre-filled message to shop owner’s WhatsApp number.
Recommended Message Format
Hello, I want to order from *{Shop Name}*.

Items:
1. {Item Name} x {Qty} - ₹{Line Total}
2. {Item Name} x {Qty} - ₹{Line Total}

Estimated Total: ₹{Cart Total}

Customer Note: {Optional Note}

Please confirm availability.

Rules
Use URL-encoded message
If no WhatsApp number is configured, hide or disable order CTA
WhatsApp CTA should still allow direct inquiry even without cart
Acceptance Criteria
Correct quantities and totals shown
Works on mobile and desktop (opens WhatsApp Web if applicable)
Handles empty cart by preventing order action

11. QR CODE REQUIREMENTS
11.1 QR Generation
Each published shop must have a QR code generated for its public storefront URL.
Requirements
Generate QR for /s/[slug]
Downloadable as PNG
Optional SVG support if easy
Regenerate when slug changes
Acceptance Criteria
QR scans resolve to correct public storefront
Owner can download QR
Admin can also access QR for support if needed

11.2 QR Poster (MVP optional but recommended)
Create a simple downloadable poster:
shop name
QR code
“Scan to view menu / catalog”
If time-constrained, this can be Phase 1.5.

12. ANALYTICS REQUIREMENTS
12.1 Owner-facing Analytics (Paid Plan)
Track at minimum:
QR scans
storefront page views
WhatsApp clicks
call clicks
share clicks
map clicks
cart add events
Optional if simple:
item views
top items by clicks
Rules
Free plan may show limited or locked analytics
Paid plan shows counters for last 7 and 30 days
Acceptance Criteria
Events recorded reliably
Analytics dashboard loads quickly
Owner only sees own shop data
Admin can see aggregated platform usage

13. SUPER ADMIN REQUIREMENTS
13.1 Admin Dashboard Capabilities
Super admin can:
view all owners
view all shops
filter by status / plan / date
activate/deactivate/suspend shops
assign plans
grant free periods
create owner accounts
create shops on behalf of owners
view usage stats
flag shops/issues
impersonate owner
view admin action logs

13.2 Impersonation
Impersonation is allowed only for super admins.
Rules
Must require reason
Must create audit log entry
Must show visible banner during impersonation
Must be time-bound or explicitly ended
All write actions during impersonation should be traceable
Acceptance Criteria
Every impersonation session logged
Owner identity preserved in logs
Admin can safely exit impersonation

14. NON-FUNCTIONAL REQUIREMENTS
14.1 Performance
Public storefront should be optimized for mobile
Time to interactive should be low
Images should be optimized and lazy-loaded
Public page should support caching/revalidation
14.2 Security
RBAC on all protected routes
Owner cannot access other owner shops
Admin routes protected
Validate and sanitize all public-facing text
Rate-limit analytics endpoint if exposed publicly
Secure image upload flow
Prevent slug collisions
14.3 Reliability
Public storefront must remain accessible even if owner dashboard is unused
Invalid/deleted items should not break storefront
Suspended shops must not expose catalog

15. DATA MODEL (HIGH LEVEL)
Core Entities
User
OwnerProfile
Shop
ShopBranding
ShopHours
ShopBanner
Category
Collection
Item
ItemCollection
QRCodeAsset
Plan
ShopSubscription
AnalyticsEvent
SupportImpersonationLog
AdminActionLog
IssueFlag
Coding agent should implement relational model using PostgreSQL + Prisma.

16. RECOMMENDED BUSINESS RULES
16.1 Publish Preconditions
A shop can be published only if:
shop name exists
unique slug exists
WhatsApp or phone exists (at least one recommended)
at least 1 category exists
at least 1 item exists
active subscription exists (free or paid)
16.2 Slug Changes
If slug changes:
old public URL becomes invalid (MVP)
QR should be regenerated
analytics remain linked to shop ID, not slug
16.3 Deletion Strategy
Use soft delete or status flags where possible for:
shops
items
categories
collections
Avoid hard delete in MVP unless safe.

17. OUT OF SCOPE (DO NOT BUILD IN MVP)
Do NOT implement:
full payment gateway integration
automatic subscription billing
order management dashboard
server-side order persistence
inventory system
staff roles
customer login/accounts
reviews/ratings
coupon engine
multilingual item content
custom domains
POS integration
delivery radius logic
push notifications

18. IMPLEMENTATION ARCHITECTURE (RECOMMENDED)
18.1 Tech Stack
Next.js (App Router)
TypeScript
Prisma
PostgreSQL
Tailwind CSS
shadcn/ui
Zod
React Hook Form
Auth.js (recommended for lower cost) or Clerk
Cloudinary for image uploads
Vercel + Neon Postgres (recommended)

